<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, August 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS -- France began evacuation of hundreds of foreigners from
Kinshasa, the capital of the Democratic Republic of Congo, toward
Brazzaville from Saturday afternoon, Agence France-Presse (AFP)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Among the foreigners being evacuated are French nationals, but
also those of other nationalities, mainly Koreans, the AFP quoted
a French diplomatic source in Kinshasa as saying.
</P>
<P>
Some 700 foreigners, who were escorted in buses toward landing
stage on the Congo River, were due to cross the river on a barge
to arrive at Brazzaville, the capital of the Congo Republic, on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Some 650 soldiers of a battalion of the French troops stationed
 in the neighboring country of Gabon have been put on alert.
</P>
<P>
Two Transall C-160 military aircraft of the French troops are
ready to join the evacuation operation, according to the AFP.
(France-Kinshasa-Evacuation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- For the first time in 18 years, 760 Iranian pilgrims
crossed the border into Iraq Saturday to visit the holy sites of
the Shiite Muslims in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The group was officially seen off at the Khosrawi border point
in Kermanshah province by Iranian Minister of Culture and Islamic
Guidance Ataollah Mohajerani.
</P>
<P>
During their stay in Iraq, the pilgrims will visit holy sites
in Karbala, Najaf and Kazemyn in the south.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Mohajerani expressed hope that the
visit would consolidate bonds between the Iranian and Iraqi
nations.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Minister of Endowments and Religious Affairs Abdal-Munim
Ahmad Salih told the Iranian delegation that his country has
restored the holy sites over recent years.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached between Iran and Iraq, 3,000
Iranian and Iraqi pilgrims are to travel to either country to pay
pilgrimage to holy sites. (Iran-Iraq-Pilgrims)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif said on
Saturday that no tension exists in relations between Pakistan and
Iran.
</P>
<P>
Sharif was talking to reporters at the launching of the Special
Tractors Scheme in Lahore.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that Pakistan was trying to create
congenial conditions and he saw no reason for tension between
Pakistan and Iran, according to the official Associated Press of
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"As a friend of Iran, whatever role Pakistan played was correct
 and proper," Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government was trying to secure the release of
the Iranian diplomats allegedly held by the Taliban in northern
Afghanistan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Such gesture could not be basis of any tension between the two
countries, he added. (Pakistan-Iran-Relations) 
</P>
</TEXT>
