<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Tobacco Sector Facing Viability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 15 (Xinhua) -- President of the Zimbabwe
Tobacco Association (ZTA) Richard Tate said viability is the
single most important challenge facing the country's tobacco
producers.
</P>
<P>
In a comment in the Zimbabwe Tobacco monthly publication
released Saturday in Harare, Tate said the association was
visiting all financial institutions, including the reserve bank
to seek relief on loans.
</P>
<P>
"Bankers realize that we are in a hostile environment and they
are asking that farmers recognize the problems will not be of a
short duration," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This hostile environment is affected by high interest rates,
the five percent levy-tax and the falling rate of the Zimbabwean
Dollar, making inputs for next season more expensive," said Tate.
</P>
<P>
Tate, however, urged farmers to appreciate the situation and
find workable solutions.
</P>
<P>
He added that the tobacco growers are facing viability
problems due to a slump in the prices of tobacco this season,
high import duty sur-charges, sales tax and the five percent
levies.
</P>
<P>
The tumble in the Southeast Asian economies leading to delays
and cancellation of tobacco orders had also affected the industry
badly, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco is one of the largest foreign currency earners with
1,700 large scale commercial growers producing 224 million
kilograms from 86,000 hectares of land while 6,000 small growers
produce six million kilograms from 6,000 hectares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
