<HEADLINE> Elephants Vandalize Irrigation Scheme in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 15 (Xinhua) -- About 30 hectares of the newly
rehabilitated Chikwalakwala irrigation scheme in south Zimbabwe
has been vandalized by elephants, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the agency, district administrator John
Brown Ncube said, "soon after the completion of rehabilitation of
this scheme, we thought that we will help alleviate food
shortages through making people sustain themselves, but all our
efforts have been brought down to nothing and we do not know
where we will get the money from to reconstruct those canals
again."
</P>
<P>
"No cropping is going on at the moment and it is a real sad
state of affairs," he said.
</P>
<P>
The irrigation scheme had produced a good crop last season and
had given high hopes to the communities that if fully utilized,
it would help alleviate food shortages which was crippling the
whole district of more than 120,000 people.
</P>
<P>
For the past weeks, elephants have caused havoc on some
commercial farms in the area raising concern among the villagers
in other irrigation schemes that they might also face the same
fate, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
