<HEADLINE> African Museum Professionals Meet in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Over 20 museum professionals
from 12 African countries are in Zimbabwe's eastern border city
of Mutare attending a three-week workshop aimed at improving
their skills on making museums more lively and relevant to local
communities.
</P>
<P>
The Museum Enlivening Skills Workshop which started on August
2 is being attended by professionals charged with the
responsibility of carrying out research work, providing education
and exhibiting museum materials in their countries, the Zimbabwe
News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Participants are from Nigeria, Ghana, Gambia, Kenya, Tanzania,
Botswana, Namibia, Malawi, Swaziland, South Africa, Zambia and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Ivan Murambiwa, regional director of the National Museums and
Monuments of Zimbabwe, told the agency the workshop was part of
an ambitious programs for International Center for Conservation
in Rome (ICCROM) and the Prevention in Museums of Africa (PREMA)
to strengthen the collection, preservation and presentation of
African museum materials.
</P>
<P>
The ICCROM is an international organization created by the
United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization
(UNESCO) in 1959 to study and research the conservation of
cultural heritage worldwide.
</P>
<P>
"The workshop also enabled us to share ideas on how to fight
the problem of the on-going plundering of Africa's cultural
heritage by people from developed countries," said Kaingu Kalume
Tinga from Kenya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
