<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The revenue of the Jordan Telecommunication Company
(JTC) this year is expected to reach 189 million Jordan dinars
(267 million U.S. dollars), a 12 percent rise over 1997, the
semi-official Jordan Times reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
JTC Chairman of Board Ali Shukri said the rise of profits would
be made possible through running new projects that have been
approved recently by the government.
</P>
<P>
The JTC will provide services in the fields of fixed
telephony, GSM mobiles and data communications, Shukri said,
adding that eight new value-added services in other fields will
also help harvest income.
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH -- The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) has
criticized non-Palestinian banks in the Palestinian self-rule
areas for making investments in other countries, the Arabic daily
Al Hayat reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a workshop here on a development plan of the
Palestinians for the coming three years, a senior official from
the PNA's Planning and International Cooperation said the
non-Palestinian banks have a saving of 2.3 billion dollars, but
they have invested 70 percent of the saving outside the
Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- It is estimated that Saudi Arabia has lost 48.8
billion Saudi riyals (13 billion dollars) in the oil revenue due
to the slump of world oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The Al Hayat newspaper said the loss of the oil revenue eats
into 29.2 percent of the expected revenue of 166.7 billion riyals
(44.4 billion dollars) based on 14 dollars per barrel of oil.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- In the Yemeni cities of Sanaa, Hudaida and Taez, 37
plants have been closed and eight others are stumbling as a result
of random measures including liberalization, opening markets,
smuggling and custom rebates, according to the Yemeni Manufacturer
Federation.
</P>
<P>
A federation official told the Al Hayat newspaper that other
enterprises have the same worry after laying off thousands of
workers, threatening the national industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
