<HEADLINE> US to Rebuild Bomb-Shattered Embassies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said on Saturday that the United States would rebuild embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania, which had been devastated by bomb attacks.
</P>
<P>
"We now must work to rebuild our embassies in Nairobi and Dar
es Salaam, to secure our embassies and outposts around the
world, to support our friends in Tanzania and Kenya as they
rebuild," Clinton said in his weekly radio address.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States "will remain committed to the fight
against terror."
</P>
<P>
He also pledged to try every effort to find those responsible
for the bombings in Kenya and Tanzania last Friday, which killed
more than 250 people, including 12 Americans, and injured over
5,000.
</P>
<P>
The United States has offered 2 million U.S. dollars for
information that leads to arrest of the bombers.
</P>
<P>
Clinton thanked Kenyans and Tanzanians for their
extraordinary efforts to pull people from the wreckage, aid the
wounded and search for evidence of who detonated the bombs.
</P>
</TEXT>
