<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Economic Reform Bears Fruits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's economic reform since
1989 has born fruits by reducing its foreign debts and increasing
the foreign reserves, the Jordanian official news agency PETRA
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Till now, Jordan's foreign debts have declined by a record 24
percent to 6.5 billion U.S. dollars from 8.5 billion U.S. dollars
before the reform was launched in 1989, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's economic reform program is co-sponsored by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank (WB).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the economic reform has increased Jordan's foreign
currency reserves to 1.6 billion dollars, compared to only 50
million dollars in 1989. The huge amount of foreign reserves have
helped fix the exchange rate between the U.S. dollar and Jordanian
currency dinar.
</P>
<P>
Both the decrease of foreign debts and the increase of foreign
reserves have played an important roles in lowering the inflation
rate and attracting foreign investment and financial aid, Jawad
Hadeed, director-general of Jordan's largest private bank the Arab
Banking Corporation, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
And the reform has also helped restore economic balance for the
kingdom and increase the world's trust in Jordan's economy as well
as its potential of growth, Hadeed added.
</P>
<P>
Banking analysts told Xinhua here Saturday that Hadeed's
comments showed that many people from the private sector are
satisfied with the government's economic reform program.
</P>
<P>
Hadeed, whose corporation also opens several banks in European
and Middle East countries, is widely regarded as an important
representative of the kingdom's private sector.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, short of natural resources and without any oil
deposit, introduced the IMF-WB economic reform nine years ago to
better structure its economy.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's economy, which featured burgeoning banking services,
booming tourism, huge remittance by expatriates and robust service
industry before the Gulf crisis in 1990, began to slump after the
crisis due to continued regional instability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
