<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Hopeful of Settling POW Issue With Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 15 (Xinhua) -- As a group of Iranian pilgrims
arriving in Iraq, Iraq said Saturday it expected to settle the
issue of Prisoner of War (POW) with Iran within this year.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency quoted charge d'affaires of the Iraqi
Embassy in Tehran Salah al-Samarmad as saying that Iraq and Iran
are now on the way of settling all pending issues, particularly
the issue of POWs.
</P>
<P>
He said all the issues are expected to be settled within the
year, and Iraq was hopeful that its relations with Iran, its
former enemy with which it fought an eight-year-long war from 1980
to 1988, "would take on a new look in the future."
</P>
<P>
The POW issue has been one of the leading obstacles that block
the normalization of ties between Iraq and Iran. The two sides
repatriated around 6,000 POWs in April this year in the largest
swap of POWs since 1991.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's optimism was voiced at a time when a group of about 760
Iranian pilgrims, led by Minister of Culture and Islamic Guidance
Ataollah Mohajerani, crossed the border into Iraq Saturday to
visit holy shrines for Shiite Muslims in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
This was the first group of Iranian pilgrims that have entered
Iraq in the past 18 years since the beginning of the Iran-Iraq war
in 1980.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian move is viewed as a new step to further improve the
bilateral relations with Iraq. In the past, Iranian government did
not allow Iranian citizens to go to Iraq to visit the holy
shrines, citing security reasons.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the departure ceremony held at a
border point, Mohajerani said the visit was the best way to
enhance cooperation between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Iraq's Minister of Endowment and Religious
Affairs Abdal-Munim Ahmed Salih voiced optimism that the
neighborly Islamic relations between Iraq and Iran could be
improved with the latest visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
