<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moscow not Allow Chechnya to Join World Community </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian envoy to the Commonwealth
of Independent States (CIS) Ivan Rybkin on Saturday said that
"Chechnya can join the international community only as a member of
Russian Federation," the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Ekho Moskvy radio station broadcast
live Rybkin said that the recent trip by the Chechen President
Aslan Maskhadov to Turkey and the United States can prove that "no
one needs Chechnya but Russia".
</P>
<P>
On Maskhadov's statement that Turkish and U.S.leading
businesses are ready to facilitate Chechnya's integration into the
world community, Rybkin noted that only those who are against
Russia's guarantees can provide finances for Chechnya's problems.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the situation in Afghanistan, the envoy said
that Moscow is not indifferent to what is going on in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
If the Taliban fighters cross the CIS border, "Russia will
retaliate with all the might it has," said Rybkin. The collective
security treaty does not allow Russia to withdraw its troops.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Foreign Ministry maintains contact with both
conflicting sides in Afghanistan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Rybkin believed that sooner or later the situation in that
region could reach a certain level of stability.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban forces recently launched massive attacks on the
opposition alliance in the northern Afghanistan bordering with
some CIS states, that brought to Russia's great attention.
</P>
</TEXT>
