<DOCNO> XIE19980816.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Opposition Leaders Begin Meetings in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Opposition leaders of Sudan began
their meetings here Saturday under the Egyptian host to discuss
ways of ending the 15-year-long civil war in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the board of the Sudanese National Democratic
Alliance (NDA), the umbrella group of opposition factions in the
north and south, was attended by various political, social and
military opposition groups.
</P>
<P>
It was chaired by DNA's leader Mohammed Osman Al-Merghani and
attened by other major opposition figures such as John Garang,
leader of the Sudanese People's Liberation Army (SPLA) and
Al-Sadeq Al-Mahdi, former Sudanese Prime Minister and leader of
the Ummah Party.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, the participants reviewed the outcome of the talks
held between Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and the Sudanese
party leaders on efforts to end Sudan civil war and ease
sufferings of residents living in the famine-stricken south.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, when meeting the rebel leaders in the northern resort
of Alexandria on Wednesday, stressed the necessity of maintaining
Sudan's unity and reinforcing efforts to end decades of fighting
in this neighboring state.
</P>
<P>
DNA spokesman Farouk Abu Isa said that the participants
confirmed their commitment to maintaining Sudan's territorial
integrity.
</P>
<P>
In the coming two days, the opposition leaders will discuss the
political situation in Sudan, the regional and international
stance toward the reconciliation process in Sudan, and compulsory
conscription by the Sudanese government of young Sudanese.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo conference followed the collapse of the peace talks
between Khartoum and the opposition alliance in Ethiopia last week.
</P>
<P>
It also came at a time when the war between the government
troops and rebel forces fighting for autonomy in southern Sudan is
escalating and famine has claimed more than 1.5 million lives.
</P>
<P>
A number of Sudanese factions, who started to arrive in Cairo a
week ago, have praised Egypt's efforts in achieving the stability
and unity of Sudan.
</P>
<P>
They said that Cairo agreement to host their gathering signaled a
major shift in Egyptian policy in their favor.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Sudan have been at odds over a border dispute and
accusing each other of harboring its opposition with the aim of
overthrowing the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
