<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Embezzlement Case Revealed in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Iran (CBI)
has uncovered an embezzlement case involving 35 billion Iran rials
(11.7 million U.S. dollars) related to the conservative judiciary,
the evening newspaper Tous reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The pro-moderate paper quoted a well-informed CBI source as
saying that the CBI has reported its findings to Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami, and the bank and the ministries of economy and
justice would further investigate the case.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in 1995, 20 billion rials (about 6.7
million dollars) were drawn out of a bank account of the Ministry
of Justice and late deposited into four personal accounts of Ali
Razini, head of the Justice Department of Tehran province.
</P>
<P>
Another 15 billion rials (5 million dollars) were withdrawn
from the same account on March 13, 1997 and also put into Razini's
private accounts, it added.
</P>
<P>
The CBI also found that Razini had another bank account with 15
billion rials of interests before July 22, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said the ministry's bank account has been under
direct supervision of Iran's judiciary chief Ayatollah Mohammad
Yazdi, who is viewed as a conservative.
</P>
<P>
If proved true, this will be the second serious embezzlement
case in the country, which may trigger another round of political
struggle between the moderates and conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Last month, former Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi, a
staunch supporter of the moderate president, was convicted of
embezzlement and sentenced to five years in imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
The moderates believed that the case was used by the
conservatives with political motivation to weaken the position of
Khatami, who advocates reforms and social freedom.
</P>
<P>
But the conservatives maintained that any one convicted of
crimes should be punished according to laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
