<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Ethio-Djibouti Railways
has celebrated it centennary establishment, the Ethiopian Herald
newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The colorful ceremony was held here Saturday at a time when
Ethiopia has diverted to the port of Djibouti from Assab of
Eritrea as its outlet after border dispute erupted between
Ethiopia and Eritrea on May 26 this year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Ethiopian Minister of Transport and
Communications Abdulmejid Hussein said that because Ethiopia has
chosen to make its import-export transactions through the port of
Djibouti instead of Assab, the number of customers asking for
railway services has increased ever than before.
</P>
<P>
This shows that the potential of this mode of transportation
is becoming most suitable, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ali Abdela Geydid, General Manager of the Ethio-Djibouti
Railways said on his part that the establishment of the railways
has helped Ethiopia promote its foreign trade by introducing
modern transportation system.
</P>
<P>
Ali Abdo, President of Addis Ababa City Administration, said
at the ceremony that the birth, development and progress of Addis
Ababa, directly or indirectly, has been associated with the
established Ethio-Djibouti railways.
</P>
<P>
The 781-kilometer Ethio-Djibouti railways were established in
1897. 
</P>
