<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telecommunications Plays Big Role in Fighting Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Jiujiang City in east China's
Jiangxi Province has drawn wide attention from both at home and
abroad, because the Yangtze River breached its dike near the city
on August 7.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, secondary dikes at Jiangxinzhou, an island in the
Yangtze and subordinate to Jiujiang, also partially collapsed.
</P>
<P>
However, losses have been minimized because of timely and
strenuous efforts by local people and soldiers, as well as
assistance from telecommunications departments.
</P>
<P>
In Jiangxinzhou, local officials have rented 15 mobile phones
especially for guiding local anti-flood activities. "We cannot
afford to buy mobile phones, but it is worthwhile to rent these,"
said a local official.
</P>
<P>
Only one village on the island was inundated, resulting in the
deaths of two villagers. Other villages remained intact and all
the flood victims were evacuated to safer places.
</P>
<P>
In the effort to plug Jiujiang's dike, modern
telecommunications means played an effective role, officials said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 110 stationary phones, 80 mobile phones and six
mobile satellite telecommunications ground stations were provided
free of charge to assist 40,000 troops and policemen working to
repair the dike.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the telecommunications
departments have provided flood-fighters in the three worst-hit
provinces -- Hubei, Hunan and Jiangxi -- with 30 emergency
telecommunications vehicles, 50 mobile satellite
telecommunications ground stations, and large quantities of other
telecommunications equipment.
</P>
<P>
Efforts also have been made to protect major telecommunications
facilities and to open temporary telecommunications services for
flood-fighting departments.
</P>
<P>
In places where flood victims congregated, local
telecommunications departments set up temporary facilities,
including a short free-of-charge service to let victims send
messages to their kin and loved ones.
</P>
<P>
In many flood-devastated areas, telecommunications offices are
often the only operational public services. They have been called
by some people an "indestructible defense line." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
