<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at GMT 15:00, August 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- Two separate arson attacks were launched against two
shops in Belfast, Northern Ireland, following Saturday's massive
car bomb blast in nearby Omagh city, killing 28 people and
injuring more than 200 others.
</P>
<P>
A BBC television report said that incendiary devices in a
clothes shop in Belfast's Cormarket area went off in the early
hours of Sunday morning, causing serious damage to the shop in one
of the two attacks.
</P>
<P>
The other attack was targeted at a music shop of the Northern
Irish capital at similar time and a British police patrol, rushing
to the scene, managed to put out the fire. (UK-NIreland-Arson
Attacks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair Sunday interrupted
his summer holiday in France and is flying to Northern Ireland
following Saturday's massive car bomb blast, killing at least 28
people and injuring 220 others.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman told reporters Sunday morning that
Blair is due to hold a series of meetings with leading politicians
in Northern Ireland later Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister is also expected to speak by telephone to
Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern and U.S. President Bill Clinton
to exchange views on the situation in Nothern Ireland, the
spokesman said. (Ulster-Explosion-Blair)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Afghanistan's Islamic Taliban gained a foothold
in Badakhshan province, a stronghold of former Afghan president
Burhanuddin Rabbani which is on the border with Tajikistan,
reports reaching here said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic militia had won the loyalty of local commanders in
the districts of Ragh, Yaftal-i-Sofla and Sheghnan in the
northeastern region, the reports said. (Afghan-Taliban)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- American and European embassies in Nigeria have
adopted extra security measures to beef up their security system
in a bid to forestall terrorist acts following the bomb blasts in
Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Some of the embassies have now resorted to scrutinizing
visitors who daily come to the embassies for visas while others
have beefed up their security system by involving additional
security operations from Nigerian police, the Post Express
newspaper reported Sunday. (Nigeria-Embassies-Security) 
</P>
