<HEADLINE> Li Peng Inspects Flooded Areas in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of the Standing
Committee of the Chinese National People's Congress (NPC),
inspected flooded areas in northernmost Heilongjiang Province
Saturday and today.
</P>
<P>
He extended warm regards and paid high tribute to the civilians
and soldiers who are fighting the floods on the Nenjiang and
Songhua rivers, two major rivers in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
So far this summer, the industrial city of Qiqihar has suffered
four floods on the Nenjiang, the most in history, which have
caused huge losses, affected millions of residents, disrupted many
sections of the Binzhou railway and threatened the safety of
Qiqihar and Daqing, where China's largest oil field is located.
</P>
<P>
Flooding of the Nenjiang River is far from over and the
flood-control task remains formidable, said Li, who is also a
member of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the
CPC Central Committee, in addressing the soldiers and civilians on
the forefront of fighting floods.
</P>
<P>
"Continued efforts must be made to counter floods and protect
the safety of the people's lives and property and to protect the
safety of Qiqihar and Daqing," Li said.
</P>
<P>
After leaving Qiqihar, Li rushed to the banks of the Songhua
River in Harbin, the provincial capital. The river's water level
of 119 meters was just four steps away from the top of the
embankment.
</P>
<P>
The water level in Harbin is expected to exceed the record high
of 120.3 meters in 1957, and the city should keep on high alert
and prepare for the worst, Li said.
</P>
<P>
"With the firm leadership of the Party Central Committee, the
support of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA) and the
effort of tens of millions of civilians, we are certain to score
victories in flood control," Li told the local residents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
