<HEADLINE> Pak Officials Rush to Afghanistan for Iranian Diplomats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 16 (Xinhua) -- A group of senior Pakistani
diplomats Sunday rushed to Afghanistan to ascertain the
whereabouts of 11 Iranian diplomats who have been missing since
the Taliban captured Mazar-e-Sharif last week.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani ambassador to Afghanistan Aziz Khan and the Director
on Afghanistan Affairs in the Foreign Office, Ayaz Wazir, went to
the Taliban's southern stronghold of Kandahar and held talks with
the militia leadership on the issue, reported the independent News
Network International(NNI).
</P>
<P>
The diplomats made the trip amidst growing tension between
Pakistan and Iran over the disappearance of the Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Iran has repeatedly requested Pakistan to help ensure the
security of its diplomats, allegedly ransacked by the hardline
Taliban when they captured Mazar-e-Sharif, stronghold of the
opposition northern alliance on August 8.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani ambassador to Iran was summoned to the Iranian
Foreign Ministry last week and was told that the Taliban and
Pakistan should take responsibility for the missing of the
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan recognizes the Taliban regime while Iran accepts the
northern alliance government led by former Afghan president
Burhannuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has rejected Iran's accusation saying it cannot be
held responsible. However, it pledged to help track down the
missing Iranians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
