<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Govt.-Formation Meeting Postponed Again in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The National Coordination
Committee of Somalia Sunday announced the postponement of the
anticipated Baidoa meeting for the formation of a government of
national unity for the third time.
</P>
<P>
According to the secretariat of the committee, the earlier
time set for the convening of the Baidoa meeting which expired
Saturday has been extended for another 135 days, which will fall
on January 1 next year.
</P>
<P>
In a press release by the committee co-chaired by Ali Mahdi
and Hussein Aidid, the delay of the anticipated Baidoa meeting is
motivated by what is called lack of funds and the completion of
Mogadishu 16-district administration.
</P>
<P>
The committee also said that a technical commission is now
formulated for the search of those funds from the Arab League,
Islamic Conference, the Organization of African Unity (OAU) and
the Inter-Governmental Authority for Development.
</P>
<P>
Another commission working on the public awareness program is
also being mobilized throughout the country as they put it.
</P>
<P>
The national coordination committee has also addressed a plea
for help in materializing the Cairo peace deal signed by 28
Somali politicians including Mahdi, Aidid, Osman Ali Atto and
Mohamed Qanyare Afrah in late December last year.
</P>
<P>
The meeting at the new headquarters of the disputed Mogadishu
administration was convened at the absence of Aidid who since
August 5 remains abroad for allegedly improving the external
relations with the Cairo agreement sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
Faction leader Atto, who together with General Mohamed Sheikh
Osman dismissed the administration of Mogadishu by Mahdi and
Aidid, has now declared the Cairo peace deal a total failure now.
</P>
<P>
"The Cairo peace deal is foiled by the continuous presence of
Hussein Aidid's militiamen in Bay and Bakol regions which is
contrary to what was signed in Cairo," said Atto.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the reporters in Mogadishu Saturday, Atto said
that the hope for a meeting in Baidoa is now dead and the Somalis
in collaboration with the international community are thinking of
holding a national reconciliation conference, but he did not
mention when, where or how.
</P>
<P>
Atto also accused Mahdi and Aidid of hijacking the
administration of Mogadishu, saying that the two have gone far
beyond justice and what they have founded is non-representative.
</P>
<P>
"There are entire clans and sub-clans who are not given their
share in the administration," said Atto.
</P>
<P>
Mogadishu is very calm, but there are speculations that clashes
might occur between Atto's sympathizers and those of Mahdi and
Aidid who are now leading the disputed administration of the
capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
