<HEADLINE> Water Level Higher on Yangtze, Nenjiang Rivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Another surge of rain-fed
flooding on the upper reaches of the Yangtze River pushed the
water level at Shashi to 44.82 meters at 2 p.m. today, 0.54 meters
higher than Monday's level, and the water level is still rising.
</P>
<P>
The water level at Hankou, part of the leading industrial
center of Wuhan, climbed to 28.91 meters today while that in
Jiujiang in east China's Jiangxi Province rose to 22.44 meters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in the country's northeastern part, the water level
at Dalai Hydrological Station, rose to 131.47 meters, 1.27 meters
above the highest recorded level, with a flow rate of 16,100 cubic
meters per second when a flood crest passed today.
</P>
<P>
By 2 p.m. today, the water level at Harbin, the provincial
capital of Heilongjiang Province which sits on the mainstream of
Songhua River, rose to 119.74 meters, 1.64 meters above the danger
mark. The flow rate was 11,700 cubic meters per second.  
</P>
</TEXT>
