<DOCNO> XIE19980816.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Embassies in Nigeria Tighten Security to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 16 (Xinhua) -- American and European embassies
in Nigeria have adopted extra security measures to beef up their
security system in a bid to forestall terrorist acts following
the bomb blasts in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Some of the embassies have now resorted to scrutinizing
visitors who daily come to the embassies for visas while others
have beefed up their security system by involving additional
security operations from Nigerian police, the Post Express
newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Close circuit monitors have been installed in the U.S. Embassy
in Lagos to monitor all activities of visitors while those who
want to get into the embassy are seriously screened with metal
detector to ensure that such persons are not in possession of any
explosives or dangerous weapons.
</P>
<P>
Security at the entrance of the U.S. Information Service based
in Lagos have been overhauled as visitors now face serious
scrutiny before getting entry into the premise.
</P>
<P>
At the British Embassy in Lagos, visitors are now subjected to
various security measures before being allowed into its premises
while those who have no genuine business around the embassy are
politely turned back.
</P>
<P>
It was observed that vehicles are not allowed to park close to
the embassies and commercial vehicles are directed to park a few
meters away before depositing their passengers, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
These beefed-up security measures have been taken at the
embassies of west countries in the wake of the bombings which
occurred on August 7 in Kenyan capital Nairobi and Tanzanian
capital Dar es Salaam, killing at least 247 people including 12
American citizens.
</P>
<P>
The local paper quoted a U.S. expert on anti-terrorism as
attributing the delay in apprehending the real culprits to the
porous security of the border in most African countries.
</P>
<P>
"African countries are loose in relation to the porous nature
of their borders", the expert said, adding that the free entry of
persons into these countries is fraught with the danger of
terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, the paper said, this is a situation that does
not augur well for the effective monitoring of terrorist attacks
in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
