<HEADLINE> Irish PM Convenes Urgent Meeting on Omagh Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern
is to hold an emergency meeting of top government officials later
Sunday to assess the security situation following the huge bomb
blast in Northern Irish town of Omagh.
</P>
<P>
An Irish government spokesman said in Dublin that the meeting
is to focus on Republican factions, which are opposed to Northern
Ireland peace agreement designed to put an end to decades of
sectarian bloodshed in the British province.
</P>
<P>
Latest reports said the bombing has killed at least 28 people
and injured 220 others.
</P>
<P>
Some senior government officials were cutting short their
summer holidays abroad and urgently returned to Dublin for the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ahern, in a strong-worded statement issued Saturday night,
condemned the Omagh blast, calling it an "dastardly incident."
</P>
<P>
"We will not be found wanting in ensuring that no organization
in our jurisdiction can continue to defy the will of the Irish
people. Those who seek to do so will be ruthlessly suppressed," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ahern' British counterpart Tony Blair, who
interrupted his holiday in France and is flying to the Omagh blast
scene, is due to hold phone talks with Ahern and U.S. President
Bill Clinton to review the situation in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The Irish police, working closely with British police, have
stepped up their surveillance of known Republican dissidents.
</P>
</TEXT>
