<HEADLINE> HK TV Show Raises 7.7 Million US Dollars for Mainland Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 16 (Xinhua) -- A six-hour overnight TV show
staged in Hong Kong obtained some 60 million HK dollars (7.7
million U.S. dollars) in donations for victims of the severe
floods along the Yangtze River on China's mainland.
</P>
<P>
The TV show was sponsored by Hong Kong's Television Broadcast
Ltd. (TVB) and two local charitable organizations, the Tung Wah
Group of Hospitals and the Yan Chai Hospital.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the show at 2:30 Sunday morning, some 30 million
HK dollars (3.8 million U.S. dollars) had been received. Plus the
same amount of donation promised by the Hong Kong Jockey Club, the
total sum added up to some 60 million HK dollars.
</P>
<P>
Before the show began at 8:30 Saturday evening, Tung Chee Hwa,
chief executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR), called on local residents to offer assistance to the flood
victims on the mainland. He also said he was proud of the
charitable activities of the Hong Kong residents.
</P>
<P>
Local artists as well as artists from the mainland and Taiwan
gave excellent performances at the show and the residents
responded enthusiastically to the appeal for donations.
</P>
<P>
In the past weeks helpful Hong Kong residents from all walks of
life have been making donations through different channels to help
their flood-stricken compatriots in the interior areas. 
</P>
