<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Ban Transfer of Outmoded Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Equipment, which does not meet the
Vietnamese standard for labor safety, environment and human health
will not be allowed into the country, Vietnam News Agency reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government has issued a decree on technology
transfer into Vietnam, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
According to the decree, those items, which have bad effects on
Vietnamese culture and national security, and do not operate
effectively will be also banned.
</P>
<P>
The decree also stipulates that commitments on technology
transfer must be made in written form which has a legal basis for
the two sides to settle any disputes.
</P>
<P>
The decree strictly regulates tariffs on imported technology
which are based on equipment bidding, and methods of payments.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency said imported equipment and
transferred technology have developed into "a headache" for the
Ministry of Science, Technology and Environment.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said after years of non-selective imports of
production lines and equipment, manufacturing quality, labor
safety and the environment are all starting to feel the impact.
</P>
<P>
according to ministry, manufacturing equipment in Vietnam is
"50-100 years out of date compared with regional countries."
</P>
<P>
The technology of the electronics, automobile, construction and
seafood processing industries is often one or two generations
behind.
</P>
<P>
The situation is worse with electricity, textile, garment,
railway, road and ship building industries.
</P>
<P>
The news agency said half of the nation's imported equipment
came from developing countries, due to lack of capital.
</P>
<P>
Even discarded equipment from developed countries made its way
into Vietnam through loopholes in appraising foreign direct
investment projects.
</P>
<P>
To avoid the risk of lagging too far behind other developing
countries in the region, the ministry said Vietnam should import
equipment and technology from developed countries, and limit
imports of second-hand equipment and outmoded technology from
other developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980816.0064 </DOCNO>
