<DOCNO> XIE19980816.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 08:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Turn War-Ruined Island to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Failaka, a Kuwaiti island
devastated during the 1990 Gulf War, is expected to become a
tourist resort within years.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwait Municipality had finalized preliminary plans to
develop Failaka, the country's second largest Gulf island, as a
tourist destination, local English daily Arab Times reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to Waleed Al-Jassim, manager of the master plan, the
island could become an international tourist destination mainly by
offering maritime, cultural and recreational facilities in its
original rustic setting.
</P>
<P>
The plan envisages developing a holiday village on the
southern coast comprising a hotel, chalets, a marina for boats
and camping sites set back from the beach and connected by
footpaths and unpaved tracks.
</P>
<P>
Water sports and boating, beach activities and fishing are
also encouraged. There will be public beaches on the south and
north western coast, while on the island itself facilities will
be built for walking, cycling, golf and a health club.
</P>
<P>
The plan focuses on Failaka's promotion as a cultural and
historical dimension by building two "archaeological parks." One
will encompass the ruins and the Muslim shrine in the center
of the island, and the other will contain the archaeological
site at the south-western corner.
</P>
<P>
The island will also provide community services such as shops,
playground, restaurants and family areas, according to the plan.
</P>
<P>
Since vehicles will be barred from accessing most areas of the
island, pedestrian and cycle paths and possibly some form of
public transportation will instead allow visitors to move across
the island.
</P>
<P>
But parties involved in this project are still divided over
the matter of cross strait transportation, with most of them
prefer to see a bridge to connect the island to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Failaka, an island at the entrance of the Kuwait Bay adjacent
to Kuwait City, was reduced to ruins during the 1990 Iraqi
invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Since the Kuwaiti government decided not to rebuild the island
after the war, there are no civilians residing on it.
</P>
<P>
According to Al-Jassim, the plan has been submitted to the
Ministry of Planning and is subject to the ministry's final
approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980816.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Diamond Industry Facing Worst Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The South African diamond
industry is facing its worst crisis this decade because of the
crash of Asian financial markets, Sunday Times reported.
</P>
<P>
The industry, which has been in depression this decade, could
expect further knocks unless conditions improve in the East,
industry officials warned.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's De Beers, the world's largest diamond mining
company, reported this week that Hong Kong's polished diamond
imports, regarded as an Asian economic indicator, were 50 percent
down in the first six months on imports in the corresponding
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Imports in Japan, the second largest market for diamonds, also
fell by 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts believed that no immediate improvement is
expected in Asia and De Beers is hanging its hat on the U.S.
market. However, the full impact of the Asian economic crisis on
the U.S. market has still to be taken into account.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that U.S. polished diamond imports have
increased and are running at 30 percent ahead of last year, but
the rise has not been strong enough to offset the decline in the
world markets.
</P>
<P>
Beside, a tumble in the U.S. stock market could also increase
the depression in the diamond market.
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing that De Beers can do if that happens," said
a diamond analyst in the company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980816.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Lanka Party Launches Campaign Against Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's People's Liberation
Front (JVP) has announced a massive agitation campaign against the
postponement of the Provincial Council Elections (PCE), JVP
sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During the week-long nationwide campaign from August 16 to 22,
a thousand meetings and door-to-door protests have been planned,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The government has postponed the polls, scheduled for August
28, on security grounds.
</P>
<P>
The JVP, an anti-government Sinhalese rebel group, was
virtually wiped out in 1989 during a bloody military sweep.
However, it has been active again in the southern region of the
country since in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The JVP attended the local government elections in March last
year and won a few seats in some local councils. 
</P>
</TEXT>
