<DOCNO> XIE19980816.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 08:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Moderates Accused for Revealing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The political struggle between
the moderates and the conservatives in Iran is likely to get tense
again as a leading conservative newspaper sharply criticized the
moderates in an embezzlement case Sunday.
</P>
<P>
After the Central Bank of Iran (CBI) revealed an embezzlement
case linking judicial officials, the Tehran Times blasted the
moderate faction for "divulging secret information" about its
rivals to suit its own interests.
</P>
<P>
"Resorting to such kinds of tactics of revealing information
to prevent checking breaches" by former Tehran Mayor
Gholamhussein Karbaschi, who was sentenced to five years in jail
for embezzlement last month,"is in contradiction with Islamic
teachings and belief," the daily said.
</P>
<P>
The CBI governor Mohsen Nourbakhsh, a member of the Party of
Constructive Executives of Iran (well-known as G-6), recently
filed a report to the Iranian President Mohammad Khatami about an
embezzlement of 35 billion rials (about 11.7 million U.S. dollars)
by judicial officials.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the amount of money was drawn out of an
account of the Justice Ministry and was put on personal accounts
of Ali Razini, head of the justice department of Tehran province,
as long-term investment deposits.
</P>
<P>
Razini also opened a personal account which has receive some 15
billion rials (about 5 million dollars) of interests from the
investment deposits, the pro-moderate evening daily Tous reported
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Tehran Times believed that at a time just before Karbaschi's
appeal to court, Nourbakhsh' move to reveal the case was aimed at
protecting the former Tehran mayor.
</P>
<P>
"Raising such an issue at this crucial time has no other
purpose than to protect Karbaschi and pave the ground for his
acquittal," the daily quoted an unnamed source as saying.
</P>
<P>
Another unnamed source was quoted as rejecting the embezzlement
charge against Razini, stating that Razini opened the account in
his personal capacity with the approval of the supreme leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
"If the money was deposited in the bank as government money, no
interest would have been paid on that," the source said, that was
the reason for Razini to open the account.
</P>
<P>
However, Nourbakhsh believed the transfer of government money
to personal accounts was illegal and asked Khatami to instruct
further investigation into the case.
</P>
<P>
It will be the second embezzlement case linking senior Iranian
officials after Karbaschi's case, which highlighted the factional
struggles between the conservatives and the moderates.
</P>
<P>
The moderates believed that the case of Karbaschi, a close
ally of Khatami, was politically motivated with an aim to weaken
Khatami's government, while the conservatives stressed that any
violator should be punished according to laws.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the new embezzlement case, if found true,
would trigger another round of confrontation between the two
rival factions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
