<HEADLINE> Taliban Gain Foothold in Northeastern Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Islamic Taliban
gained a foothold in Badakhshan province, a stronghold of former
Afghan president Burhanuddin Rabbani which is on the border with
Tajikistan, reports reaching here said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic militia had won the loyalty of local commanders in
the districts of Ragh, Yaftal-i-Sofla and Sheghnan in the
northeastern region, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban mouthpiece Radio Shariat said white flags of the
Islamic militia were now flying in various districts after the
switchover by the commanders, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani's men were fleeing the areas, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate independent confirmation of the reports
and no comment was available from the opposition side.
</P>
<P>
Badakhshan has come under pressure after the Taliban captured
the Taloqan supply base of Rabbani's military strongman Ahmad
Masood in neighboring Takhar province. 
</P>
