<HEADLINE> Uganda Considers Closing Embassy in DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government is
considering closing its embassy in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC) in the wake of a raid by DRC soldiers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
All the embassy staff are likely to be evacuated out of the
war-torn country, a Foreign Ministry source was quoted by
Sunday's Monitor newspaper as saying Saturday.
</P>
<P>
However, Sunday's New Vision, the leading daily in Uganda,
reported that Ugandan diplomats in DRC have fled across the Congo
River to Brazzaville for fear of their lives.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Ugandan embassy in DRC was attacked by some
government soldiers of DRC who forced their way into the compound
on a pick-up.
</P>
<P>
They looted properties and demanded money when putting a
diplomat at gun point. Uganda issued a protest statement to the
DRC soon after the incident.
</P>
<P>
Since August 2, the Tutsi-led soldiers have been fighting
against President Laurent Kabila. The attack erupted in Kinshasa
and quickly spread to other parts of the sprawling country, the
eastern part in particular.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Kabila forces claimed that they had already taken
one-third of the country and are now closing in on the capital.
</P>
<P>
Kabila accused Rwanda and Uganda of being behind the
rebellion, a charge the two neighbors immediately denied.
</P>
<P>
Now seven countries are evacuating their nationals from DRC.
Britain, France and the United States are sending troops there to
evacuate and protect their nationals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
