<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Villages Now Looking For Accountants Locally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 16 (Xinhua) -- In Kaiyuan City in northeast
China's Liaoning Province, village accountants are being hired for
the first time by the local government.
</P>
<P>
The accountants have passed certifying exams and have been
approved by villagers. They will have a say in all of the
village's financial matters like the raising and management of
funds. They report to their superior and are supposed to veto any
illegal financial transactions.
</P>
<P>
In the past, in most villages in China, accountants were hired
and fired by the village committee, a practice that often led to
sloppy financial practices and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen newly-appointed village accountants in Kaiyuan answer
directly to the local government and are expected to act more
independently. What is more important, though, financial affairs
that are handled by the village committee will be scrutinized by
villagers who are guaranteed access to them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
