<HEADLINE> Joint Command Set up to Fight Rebels in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Joint Operations Command
(JOC) has been re-established in Sri Lanka for the armed services
and the police to collectively plan and execute counter rebel
operations, the Sunday Times reported.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan Army Commander Rohan De.S. Daluwatte has been
appointed as the General Officer Commanding of the unified
military and police apparatus, the report quoted Defense Ministry
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the new command would gradually take up the
functions assigned, preventing any disruption of on-going counter
terrorism activity.
</P>
<P>
The decision to set up the JOC came after the government
examined various proposals for a unified approach to the issue of
countering terrorism. The idea was to utilize the resources of the
security forces to maximum, they said.
</P>
<P>
The JOC was set up for the first time when former president
Junius Richard Jayewardene was in office (1978.2-1989.1). However,
the previous government scrapped the JOC and set up a high-powered
Defense Coordinating Committee in its place in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan government troops have been fighting a war since
1983 against Tamil rebels who are fighting for a separate Tamil
state in the north and east of the island country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
