<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea to Set up EPZ in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- A South Korean firm will set up a
new export processing zone (EPZ) in Bangladesh's southeastern
seaport city of Chittagong, the South Korean Embassy in Dhaka said
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A 20-month survey for acquiring over 1,000 hectares of land for
the EPZ, the biggest to be set up by South Korea in this South
Asian country, has been completed under an agreement signed
between the two sides in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
The formal earth-breaking for the large private EPZ, which is
to be owned by South Korea's Yong Wang Corporation, is expected to
take place in November or December this year.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean firm has drawn up a plan to develop the
tree-covered and pond-dotted area, keeping natural beauty spots of
the area intact.
</P>
<P>
Besides the plot for manufacturing units, the
200-million-U.S.-dollar project will also include a small
airstrip, a recreational park, facilities for supply of safe
drinking water, a full-fledged hospital, a community center, a
golf course and an educational center. A satellite town will be
also be developed.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 industrial and manufacturing units would be
accommodated in the zone in an orderly fashion.
</P>
<P>
The units to be set up in the zone will create over 100,000
jobs, and the investment in the form of units and factories will
be over one billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government will ensure electricity, gas supply,
telephone and other infrastructure facilities for the EPZ in
accordance with the agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
