<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Bank in Trouble in Overdue Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh Krishi
(agriculture) Bank (BKB) has an overdue loan of 17.74 billion taka
(377 million U.S. dollars), which is 51 percent of the total
amount of loans it had disbursed, the Financial Express newspaper
reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
BKB's outstanding loans stood at 34.49 billion taka (734
million dollars) as of June 30, 1998, official sources were quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the bank's borrowings from Bangladesh Bank,
the country's central bank, and different foreign agencies were
23.90 billion taka (509 million dollars) and 1.82 billion taka
(387 million dollars) respectively. The bank also owed 184.5
million taka (3.93 million dollars) to the government.
</P>
<P>
The heavy losses incurred by BKB over the years were attributed
to lack of accountability, trade union militancy, weak management
and corruption by the officials and use of the bank for political
purposes by the government, they said.
</P>
<P>
Inadequate and faulty evaluation of projects during the
sanction of loans had been continuing as usual, throwing the
financial institution into dire straits, they added.
</P>
<P>
BKB incurred losses of 768 million taka (16.3 million dollars),
746 million taka (15.9 million dollars) and 1.1 billion taka (23.4
million dollars) respectively in the 1995-96, 1996-97 and 1997-98
fiscal years.
</P>
<P>
BKB has branches in the country's 49 districts, and 44 of them
have incurred losses, with only five earning marginal profits.
</P>
<P>
At present, the bank has only 1.8 billion (38.3 million
dollars) of running capital against the requirement of 3.5 billion
taka (74.5 million dollars), according to the central bank's
latest report.
</P>
<P>
The bank recovered 8.81 billion taka (187.4 million dollars)
against the target of 11 billion taka (234 million dollars) during
the July 1997-June 1998 fiscal year, while the amount of its
disbursement was 8.49 billion taka (180.6 million dollars) against
the target of 10 billion taka (212.8 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
To resolve the issue of BKB's poor performance, Finance
Minister A.S.M. Kabria recently asked the bank to get rid of trade
union activities and implement reform programs to enhance its
efficiency and remove irregularities in the loan disbursement
process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
