<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The infiltration of the Soujud outpost in the security zone
in south Lebanon last Sunday by a Hezbollah gunman who then
escaped alive was a "serious operational failure," Israel's Chief
of General Staff Lt. Gen. Shaul Mofaz said.
</P>
<P>
Following his own summary inquiry into the incident, Mofaz
ordered that disciplinary action be taken against three Israeli
paratroopers involved.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- The political tension between Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai rose another
notch over the weekend with Netanyahu reportedly being furious
with Mordechai for "arguing about honor."
</P>
<P>
The defense minister is boiling mad that Netanyahu decided to
name a new candidate to represent Likud in the Tiberias mayoral
race, slighting Mordechai's brother, Motti, who had won the No.2
spot in a local internal party vote but was passed over by
Netanyahu, sources close to Mordechai said.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Senior officers in Israel's Northern Command are critical
of Mofaz's decision to reprimand the three paratroopers -- an
officer and two soldiers -- involved in the so-called "Soujud
fiasco."
</P>
<P>
Mofaz, who said the first duty of the soldiers was to kill the
Hezbollah infiltrator, has instructed that the reprimands be noted
in their records. 
</P>
