<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Province to Invest Heavily in Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 16 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang Province
will increase investment in infrastructure by 10 billion yuan
this year in order to increase demand and to realize an
economic growth rate of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
This move is being taken by the prosperous province to
counteract the negative effects of the financial crisis in
Southeast Asia, according to Shao Qianlong, an official with the
Zhejiang Provincial Planning and Economic Commission.
</P>
<P>
Shao said that some 36 local infrastructure projects will have
sufficient funding this year. These are projects related to water
conservancy, railways, highways, electricity, environmental
protection and housing.
</P>
<P>
The province has set a goal of building seawalls, highways and
river embarkments within the next few years, all of which will be
at least 1,000 kilometers long. It will also construct an airport
with a handling capacity of 10 million passengers a year and
increase its installed generation capacity by 10 million kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
Both the central and local governments will adopt favorable
policies to encourage domestic and overseas companies to invest
in these infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, 1998, the province has invested 18.4
billion yuan in local infrastructure projects, up 30 percent from
the same period last year, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The province's total fixed-asset investment is projected to
increase by 12 percent this year, with investment in
infrastructure up 18 percent, Shao said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
