<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0530 GMT, August 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS -- The Venezuelan Aluminum Complex will be put on
auction in September, the third attempt this year to privatize the
enterprise plagued by mounting losses, the El Universal newspaper
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The base price for the complex is set at 207 million
U.S. dollars while registration of bidders will start next Monday
and end on August 27, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The previous two auction attempts failed as bidders complained
that the base prices of 2.1 billion and 1.55 billion dollars were
too high. (Venezuela-Auction-Aluminum Complex)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syria and the European Union (EU) signed Saturday a
framework agreement under which the EU will provide Syria with
loans and technical aid to enhance their partnership.
</P>
<P>
Syria will receive 65 million U.S. dollars of grants from the
EU and a loan of 250 million U.S. dollars from the European
Investment Bank, in addition to 200 million U.S. dollars worth of
EU technical assistance. (Syria-EU-Aid Agreement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's economic reform since 1989 has born fruits by
reducing its foreign debts and increasing the foreign reserves,
the Jordanian official news agency PETRA reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Till now, Jordan's foreign debts have declined by a record 24
percent to 6.5 billion U.S. dollars from 8.5 billion U.S. dollars
before the reform was launched in 1989, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's economic reform program is co-sponsored by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank (WB).
(Jordan-Economy-Reform)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- Vietnam will clear the way for its full participation
in the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) plan scheduled for 2006 as it
has committed, the Vietnam News Agency Saturday quoted a
government official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has pledged to apply tariffs of up to five percent on
at least 85 percent of its goods sold in regional markets by 2006,
said deputy minister for foreign affairs, Nguyen Tam Chien.
</P>
<P>
He added that Vietnam has completed a list of 1,700 goods items
subjected to tariffs deduction, which will be applied gradually.
(Vietnam-AFTA) 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
