<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slovakia's Foreign Exchange Reserves Hit Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, Aguest 15 (Xinhua) -- Slovakia's foreign exchange
reserves reached a record high of 7.996 billion U.S. dollars by
August 12, an increase of 1.507 billion dollars from that at the
end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The National Bank also reported that its foreign reserves rose
by 573 million dollars to 3.858 billion dollars in the same period.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign exchange reserves went up steadily in
recent years. They totaled 5.686 billion dollars and 6.489 billion
dollars in 1996 and 1997 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The increase was contributed to the economic growth. The
country's gross domestic product (GDP) rose 6.8 percent, 6.9
percent and 6.1 percent respectively from 1995 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
The GDP for this year is expected to be around 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, inflation went down from 25 percent in 1993 to 6.4
percent in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
