<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lavender Oil Per Unit Output Up in Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A Bulgarian research institute has
obtained the highest per-unit output of lavender oil in 10 years,
one kilogram from 57 kilograms of lavender blossom.
</P>
<P>
The Research Institute for Roses, Aromatic and Medicinal Plants
of Kazanluk attributed its success to "the highly productive
varieties and the better farming machinery."
</P>
<P>
The 24 other distilleries in Bulgaria achieved a yield of one
kilogram of lavender oil from 100-110 kilograms of blossom.
</P>
<P>
The institute expects to produce some three tons of lavender
oil this year, said the Institute's Director Georgi Chaoushev.
</P>
<P>
He added that the customers are from the world over and the
lavender plantation has attracted investment from French and
U.S. companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980816.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Confirms Suspension of Foreigners' Sentences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government Sunday
confirmed that it had suspended the sentences, handed down on 18
foreigners by a district special court, by deporting them on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 18 foreigners -- 10 men and 8 women from the United States,
Indonesia, Malaysia, Thailand, the Philippines and Australia --
were sentenced by the court on Friday to five years' imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
The foreigners, who were charged with attempting to incite
unrest in Myanmar by distributing leaflets in Yangon, the capital
city, were then deported after the Myanmar Ministry of Home
Affairs suspended the sentences.
</P>
<P>
The official New Light of Myanmar newspaper quoted the ministry
as saying that the ministry's decision to allow the 18 foreigners
to leave was made in consideration of the fact that most of them
are from neighboring fellow member countries of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations, with which Myanmar is on existing
friendly terms.
</P>
<P>
"The 18 did not know the situation of Myanmar definitely and
they were found guilty of committing offense because of persuasion
and deception of Alternative ASEAN Network on Burma," the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
"They confessed to having committed the offense," the ministry
said, adding that requests for their release had been made by
their families and officials of respective governments.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the concerned countries including the
United States welcomed the Myanmar government's decision on the
eighteen's release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
