<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's LTTE to Free Indian Crew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam (LTTE) had agreed to free the 17 Indian crew members
from a foreign merchant ship they had hijacked, International
Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels were quoted as claiming that they were willing
to release the 17 crew members. ICRC officials began talks on
Saturday with the LTTE to secure their release, the sources told
Xinhua by telephone.
</P>
<P>
LTTE gunmen on Friday morning seized a Dubai-owed merchant ship
with 21 crew members on board, including 17 Indian nationals.
</P>
<P>
The ship was on its way to the northern peninsula of Jaffna
from Colombo when it was hijacked near Mullaithivy coast. It was
carrying cement and general cargo for traders of Jaffna city.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan Air force jets bombed the 6,000-ton ship Friday
evening in a bid to destroy it to prevent the cargo from falling
into the rebels' hands.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels claimed that they took the crew because the
ship was "violating Tamil territorial waters."
</P>
<P>
The LTTE radio Voice of Tiger announced last night that the
crew was in their custody and would be handed over to the ICRC
after interrogations were over.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to get the crew members released as soon as
possible," the ICRC sources said.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting a war against the government for a
separate Tamil state in the north and east of Sri Lanka since
1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
