<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Budget Deficit Down Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Budget deficits of Costa Rica
dropped to some 167 million dollars in the first seven months
this year, 32 percent less than the same period of last year, the
Finance Ministry said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Total government revenue in the first seven months amounted to
1.011 billions U.S. dollars, of which 99.2 percent came from
taxes, according to a report released by the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The total expenditure stood at 1.178 billion dollars, down 15.2
percent compared with the corresponding period of last year. Some
25 percent of the government spending was used to pay public
servants, 13.4 percent as pensions and 6.2 percent as funding to
universities.
</P>
<P>
The Costa Rica's budget deficits have been shrinking in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 budget deficits were reduced to 4 percent of the gross
domestic product, a further decline from the 5.2 percent in 1995.
</P>
