<HEADLINE> China's Tea Exports Rise Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- In the first half of this year
China's tea exports increased 17 percent from the same period last
year to 98,625 tons, with turnover surging 18 percent to 26.15
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that the average export tea price climbed
to 1.71 U.S. dollars per kilogram, up 0.02 U.S. dollar over last
year.
</P>
<P>
Liu Yichen, a foreign trade official in charge of tea export,
said that if there is no significant increase in tea supply on
the world market, the tea price will continue its upward trend in
the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the floods that have swept across south China, where
the country's main tea plantations are located, may have a
negative impact on the supply of tea products in the months to
come, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
(MOFTEC) issued a new regulation recently on the management of tea
exports, under the terms of which the government will no longer
apply unified management to the export of tea.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade companies and production enterprises which have
obtained the right from the MOFTEC to export tea will be able to
handle the export business by themselves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
