<HEADLINE> Clinton Condemns Bombing in Northern Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Saturday condemned a deadly bombing in Northern Ireland and
said that it must not set back the peace process there.
</P>
<P>
"On behalf of every American, I condemn this butchery and hope
that the culprits will be brought to justice quickly," said
Clinton in a statement released by the White House.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Clinton's planned visit to Northern Ireland
in early September was expected to go forward as planned despite
heightened tension.
</P>
<P>
"Today's terrorist bombing in Omagh was a barbaric act intended
to wreck Northern Ireland's aspirations for peace and
reconciliation," Clinton said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
He urged all parties to step up efforts to end the violence.
"Now is the time for the parties of peace in Northern Ireland to
redouble their efforts," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I renew my pledge to stand with the people of Northern Ireland
against the perpetrators of violence; they will find no friends
here," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton plans to visit Northern Ireland and Ireland in early
September after visiting Russia to show U.S. support for a peace
process aimed at power sharing between the contending groups.
</P>
<P>
"This (bombing) is not expected to affect his itinerary," said
P.J. Crowley, a White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
A car bomb exploded in the busy central shopping district of
the Northern Irish town of Omagh near Belfast on Saturday, killing
at least 26 people and injuring dozens more.
</P>
<P>
The explosion was the worst carnage in Northern Ireland during
30 years of violence over British rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
