<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Island Province Boosts Mining Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- South China's Hainan Province
will continue to tap the potential of its mining industry, today's
China's Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
Liang Xinnan, director of the Hainan Provincial
Mineral Resources Management Department, pointed out the progress of
Hainan's mining sector by referring to the 1996 output value of 764
million yuan (92 million U.S. dollars) from mining exploration,
and that of 2.675 billion yuan (322 million dollars) from related
mining processing industries.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the output of the island province's mining sector
stood at 800 million yuan (96 million dollars), while the figure
for the mining processing sector was 3.5 billion yuan (421 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The two sectors combined to account for 18.6 percent of
Hainan's total industrial output in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Liang called for full use of the abundant mineral resources to
boost the economy.
</P>
<P>
Hainan has 88 types of verified minerals, of which 63 are
verified industrial-value reserves with a total economic potential
of 207.4 billion yuan (25 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, Hainan's mineral exploitation sector is still in its
infancy, with only 35 of the 63 verified reserves being exploited.
</P>
<P>
Few foreign investors engaged in large-scale mining and refined
mining processing industries, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
A Mining Exploration Supervision office was established to
forbid activities such as non-government authorized exploration,
illegal mineral resource transfer and random exploitation.
</P>
</TEXT>
