<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Oil Giant Sets Ambitious Profit Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The recently reshuffled China
National Petroleum Corp (CNPC) plans to earn 2.79 billion yuan in
profits in 1998, said Ma Fucai, president of the corporation.
</P>
<P>
Ma said that this ambitious target indicates that CNPC is
trying its best to contribute to the fulfilment of the country's
eight percent economic growth goal.
</P>
<P>
Producing 67 percent of China's crude oil, CNPC recorded 10.18
billion yuan in profits and paid 22.89 billion yuan in taxes last
year.
</P>
<P>
However, CNPC has suffered formidable problems since the
beginning of 1998 due to the Asian financial turmoil and the slump
in international oil prices.
</P>
<P>
In June this year, the central government decontrolled the country's
oil pricing system, letting the prices of crude and oil products
be driven down to the levels on the international market.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, CNPC made only 150 million yuan
in profits, which was 6.24 billion yuan less than in the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Ma said the corporation has asked its oilfields to enhance
output as much as possible in the second half of this year, and
the daily oil output is targeted to reach 298,500 tons by the end
of September.
</P>
<P>
CNPC plans to produce 107.8 million tons of crude oil in
1998. It pumped 53 million tons in the first six months of this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
