<HEADLINE> Raul Cubas Assumes Paraguayan Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Raul Cubas was sworn in as
the new president of Paraguay to succeed Juan Carlos Wasmosy at a
ceremony in the Paraguayan capital of Asuncion on Saturday, said
reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The event marked the first peaceful hand-over of power from one
civilian president to another in more than 50 years in that small
country.
</P>
<P>
Cubas, 54, planning minister between 1994 and 1996, and finance
minister in 1996, won Paraguay's presidential elections on May 10.
</P>
<P>
Previously running for vice president, he was chosen by the
Colorado Party to run for the presidency after the party's former
presidential candidate Gen. Lino Oviedo was sentenced to 10 years
in prison.
</P>
<P>
Oviedo was charged by a special military court with
masterminding an attempted coup against outgoing President Wasmosy.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Colorado Party Luis Maria Argana was sworn in
as the new vice president at the same ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was attended by Argentine President Carlos Menem,
Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, Uruguayan President
Julio Maria Sanguinetti, Chilean President Eduardo Frei, Bolivian
President Hugo Banzer, Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori and
Ecuadoran President Jamil Mahuad.
</P>
<P>
Spanish Crown Prince Philip and General Secretary of the
Organization of American States Cesar Gaviria were also present.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the new president is facing serious political
and economic challenges in clearing up the mess left by his
predecessor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
