<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Crisis Won't Affect Future Of Xiamen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, August 16 (Xinhua) -- In spite of the increasing impact
of the Asian financial crisis on China, the economic prospects of
Xiamen look good, the Secretary of the Xiamen City Communist Party
Committee Shi Zhaobin told Xinhua recently.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen, a port city in Fujian Province, has been affected by
the financial crisis, Shi said, but they have managed to minimize
the effects even though the city's economy depends to a great
extent on exports and overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investment in Xiamen was 19.3 percent more in the
first quarter of this year than the same period of last year, even
though Southeast Asian investment fell 26.7 percent during the
period. January-March exports to Southeast Asia, Japan and the
Republic of Korea were down more than 40 percent, but exports
overall were up 12.3 percent on a year-on-year basis.
</P>
<P>
Shi attributed this to the city's having turned to Europe and
America for investment starting as early as in 1992, when
favorable special economic special zone policies began to lose
their appeal.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen has companies from 26 countries and regions investing in
it. European and American investment jumped eight-fold last year
and was more than double in the first quarter of this
year. Exports to Europe and America have also grown significantly.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen's GDP was 37.1 billion yuan last year, more than 24
times that in 1980, when Xiamen became a special economic zone to
pursue flexible policies to encourage investors from Taiwan, Hong
Kong and overseas.
</P>
<P>
Continued infrastructure investment of 3 billion yuan each year
on average will help Xiamen's economic growth in the future, Shi
said, adding that he is confident that its GDP will exceed 40
billion yuan by the end of the century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
