<HEADLINE> Indonesia Deeply Concerned About Afghan Civil war </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government is
deeply concerned about Afghanistan's prolonged civil war and calls
on the conflicting parties in the country to find a peaceful
solution, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government had urged the Organization of the
Islamic Conference (OIC) and the United Nations to work harder to
end the crisis, the Foreign Ministry spokesman, Gaffar Fadhyl,
said here Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia wants the safety of any foreign national, especially
diplomats who are stationed in the conflict areas, to be
guaranteed and they can return to their home countries safely," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government also urged the parties to the
conflict to restrain themselves, effect a cease fire and hold
talks soon so as to find a peaceful solution, he said.
</P>
<P>
The civil war in Afghanistan has been going on for many years.
</P>
<P>
Afghanistan's Taliban troops were reported by Afghan Islamic
Press (AIP) on Saturday to have captured the town of Doshi in
Baghlan province.
</P>
<P>
Doshi is situated close to the crucial Salang tunnel that links
the Afghan capital Kabul with the north of the country. 
