<HEADLINE> 118 Guatemalan Refugees Return Home from Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A total of 118 Guatemalan
refugees returned home on Saturday from Mexico where they had
lived for more than 14 years, said a Mexican Commission of
Assitance (COMAR) to Refugees official.
</P>
<P>
The official, Alfonso Hernandez Ortega, said that the refugees
crossed the Mexico-Guatemala border through Ciudad Cuauhtemoc-La
Mesilla, in five buses and 10 cargo trucks.
</P>
<P>
The group went home with representatives from COMAR, the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees and other non-government
organizations of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the refugees at the border, the Guatemalan
authorities promised to assist them with credits and housing so
they have a dignified and productive life.
</P>
<P>
Tomas Lucas Lucas, one of the refugees, thanked the Mexican
government for supporting them for more than 10 years and asked it
to continue assisting those who chose to remain in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Official data show that 15,500 of the 45,000 Guatemalan
refugees who came to Mexico in 1980s remain in the country and of
them 60 percent were born there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
