<HEADLINE> Financial Situation Better In Southern Chinese Island Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Financial conditions in Haikou,
the capital of China's Hainan Province, are now stable in spite of
a shortage of funds and recent shutdown of a local bank, says Wang
Faren, the City's mayor.
</P>
<P>
The Hainan Development Bank, a major local bank, was closed
because of its inability to return deposits and there was a run on
the bank when depositors began to fear financial disorder.
</P>
<P>
The bank was taken over by the Industrial and Commercial Bank
of China, one of the country's largest commercial banks, a move
that calmed local depositors, Wang says.
</P>
<P>
He says that Haikou has had positive growth in the first half
of this year, with the GDP up 8.1 percent from the same period of
last year.
</P>
<P>
Bank deposits only dropped slightly to 22 billion yuan in the
first half, and loans amounted to 20 billion yuan. 
</P>
