<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Standardizes Domestic Service Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SHANGHAI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Domestic-worker agencies in
Shanghai shall provide adequate training to prospective household
workers before sending him or her out on a job.
</P>
<P>
This requirement is part of the new regulations governing the
management of domestic-worker agencies which recently went into
effect in China's leading manufacturing center.
</P>
<P>
With living standards improving fast, the demand for domestic
workers is growing at an unprecedented rate in China's big
cities. However, the lack of market regulation has often led to
problems such as cheating and poor service.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the new regulations, domestic-worker agencies
in Shanghai must be licensed by the local labor department before
starting a business, and their operations must be confined to
finding help for families, not for organizations.
</P>
<P>
The responsibilities of the agencies also include issuing work
permits, organizing medical check-ups, providing guarantees as
required, and handling disputes between its employees and the
families they serve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
