<HEADLINE> Manchester United Draws with Leicester </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A dramatic last-gasp goal from
David Beckham saved Manchester United from defeat, making the
title contender to draw with Leicester 2-2 in the opening game of
the English Premier league on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Foxes were on course to continue their remarkable record
against United when they led 2-0 with just 12 minutes remaining,
but substitute Teddy Sheringham pulled a goal back before David
Beckham equalised with a free-kick deep into stoppage time.
</P>
<P>
Leicester boss Martin O'Neill admitted: "I'm actually very
disappointed. To be 2-0 up at Old Trafford on the opening day of
the season and despite Manchester United having the majority of
the possession in the second half, overall I thought we had the
better chances in the game. But we were never comfortable, even
at 2-0 and we just got a wee bit tired and sloppy."
</P>
<P>
United boss Alex Ferguson said:"It was a very poor, sluggish
performance from us and we can only improve."
</P>
<P>
Coventry City sent Chelsea crashing to an opening day defeat
for the second successive season, beating the much-fancied
English title challengers 2-1 with goals from Darren Huckerby and
Dion Dublin.
</P>
<P>
Chelsea, starting with nine overseas players in their line-up
including debutants Albert Ferrer of Spain, French World Cup
winner Marcel Desailly and Pierluigi Casiraghi of Italy,were 2-0
down after only 16 minutes and never recovered.
</P>
<P>
They pulled a goal back after 37 minutes when Uruguayan
Gustavo Poyet headed home a Denis Wise cross, and although
Casiraghi went close to scoring three times, Coventry, who beat
them 3-2 at Highfield Road on the opening day of last
season,still held on for the points.
</P>
<P>
Coventry manager Gordon Strachan said: "We had to work very
hard to beat them today, they are a team packed with world class
stars and they worked hard as well. But it was good to see the
moves we had worked on in training pay off."
</P>
<P>
In other matches of the day, Blackburn Rovers tied Derby
County 0-0, Everton played to a 0-0 draw against Aston Villa,
Middlesbrough tied Leeds United 0-0, Newcastle tied Charlton
Athletic 0-0,Sheffield Wednesday lost to West Ham 0-1 and
Wimbledon beat Tottenham Hotspur 3-1. 
