<HEADLINE> N.Irish Official Blames Unhanded Arsenals for Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's First Minister
David Trimble said Saturday that the bomb blast, which killed at
least 26 people in the town of Omagh, Northern Ireland, could have
been avoided if Irish republican guerrillas had handed in their
arsenals.
</P>
<P>
"Make no mistake about it, this bomb would not have been made
or been detonated if Sinn Fein/IRA had handed over its explosives
and weapons," Trimble said in a statement issued from Germany,
where he is on holiday, according to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
Trimble said the blast which ripped through a busy shopping
street was "designed to cause the maximum amount of terror".
</P>
<P>
"There is no excuse, no justification, no reason for this
murderous terrorist onslaught," he said. "This day will forever be
remembered as the worst in our history. This day will be
remembered for its savagery and its naked hatred."
</P>
<P>
Trimble, leader of the Protestant Ulster Unionist Party (UUP),
assumed his new post on July 1 as part of an agreement intended to
end 30 years of violence in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The conflict has seen violence from republican guerrillas,
drawn from the Catholic community and opposed to British rule, and
from armed groups from the Protestant majority population
determined to preserve it.
</P>
<P>
The agreement brought new optimism to the province but
Protestant opponents of the deal were angry that republicans were
allowed to benefit from it without having to hand over any of the
weapons from their vast arsenals first.  
</P>
</TEXT>
