<HEADLINE> Eyewitnesses Tell of Bomb Scene in Northern Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Eyewitnesses have told local
media the horror and chaos that followed the bomb explosion in
Omagh in Northern Ireland this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Nigel O'Kane, landlord of the Monument pub, said that "a couple
of buildings were flattened by the bomb. It's tragic. We heard the
explosion, it seemed very large. It was less than 100 yards away
from the biggest supermarket area, on the biggest shopping day of
the week."
</P>
<P>
"There were a lot of people looking for loved ones who might
have been shopping. It's just carnage, the worst possible place to
get a bomb."
</P>
<P>
Police had tried to move everybody away from the area to where
the bomb really was, after receiving a bomb threat, and about 20
minutes later the bomb blew up behind them, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dorothy Boyle, a Omagh resident, said "I saw bodies lying
everywhere, dead people being zipped into bags. The bodies were
lying there with water running over them from burst pipes. There
were limbs lying about that had been blown off people. Everyone
was running round trying to help people."
</P>
<P>
Local businessman Sean Conway said "I could see a lot of
injured people and people running everywhere, screaming and
crying, looking for their relatives, their friends, their sisters
and their brothers. It's just pandemonium."  
</P>
