<DOCNO> XIE19980816.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pattern of Recent Bombings in N. Ireland Analyzed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The bomb attack in Omagh this
afternoon fits into a pattern of bombings carried out in Northern
Ireland market towns over the past few weeks and months, which
Irish security forces believed to be the work of the Real IRA, a
splinter group, though no group has claimed responsibility for
today's explosion yet.
</P>
<P>
But unlike those attacks, which caused considerable damage to
property, the Omagh bomb today has led to carnage on a scale which
has not been seen since Enniskillen in November, 1987, or
Belfast's Shankill Road in October, 1993, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
As such, it has already plunged the province back into its
darkest days and the repercussions are likely to be far-reaching,
a BBC report said.
</P>
<P>
The Irish security forces insist that the recent bombings are
the work of dissidents - primarily, a splinter group called the
Real IRA, who, they say, have not been assisted by the IRA proper.
</P>
<P>
But many unionists and loyalists find that difficult to accept.
One loyalist politician warned earlier this month that the
loyalist ceasefire might not hold if anyone was killed by a
dissident republican bomb, according to earlier reports.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, within mainstream unionism, there has been
increasing nervousness about the release of paramilitary prisoners
and other aspects of the Good Friday agreement.
</P>
<P>
In a fortnight's time, U.S. President Clinton is due in
Northern Ireland to celebrate the achievements of the peace
process. But after this afternoon's atrocity in Omagh, ordinary
people in Northern Ireland might ask where the peace process is
going.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980816.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Preparing for Testimony in Lewinsky Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
met with his lawyers on Saturday to prepare for his grand jury
testimony.
</P>
<P>
It was likely Clinton would make a televised appearance to talk
about Monday's testimony for independent counsel Kenneth Starr's
grand jury probing the White House sex scandal, news reports
quoted unidentified White House officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
But one official said a final decision on a statement would
depend on how the president felt about it on Monday. "Nothing's
going to happen until Monday," according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will be the first sitting U.S. president to give sworn
testimony to a criminal grand jury probing his actions.
</P>
<P>
He will be questioned at the White House, with his words
transmitted live to a federal courthouse a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's private attorney, David Kendall, and Mickey Kantor,
the former Commerce secretary, were seen entering the White House
on Saturday to help prepare the president. More talks were
expected on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was expected to face tough questions about his
relationship with Lewinsky, 25, who according to sources told the
grand jury last week that she and the president had a number of
sexual encounters in the White House and discussed cover stories
to disguise their relationship.
</P>
<P>
In earlier sworn statements to lawyers in a sexual harassment
case filed against him, Clinton denied having sexual relations
with Lewinsky, now 25.
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky also denied having sex with Clinton when asked about
it by lawyers for Paula Jones, but changed her account when
brought before the grand jury after receiving blanket immunity
from prosecution by Starr.
</P>
<P>
Recent polls suggest most Americans believe Clinton had an
affair with Lewinsky. Even so, the polls show most of those
surveyed would not lose confidence in him as president.
</P>
<P>
A Newsweek poll released on Saturday said 56 percent of
Americans anticipated Clinton will not tell the whole truth in his
testimony. But only 24 percent said they would think worse of
Clinton if he admitted that he had an ongoing sexual relationship
with Lewinsky.  
</P>
</TEXT>
