<HEADLINE> Northern Ireland Explosion Death Toll Rises to 26 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- At least 26 people, instead of 21
as previously reported, including an 18-month-old infant, have
been killed in the worst paramilitary bombing since the start of
the Northern Ireland conflict 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Political leaders have been joined by the Queen in expressing
their sympathy for the bereaved and those injured in the explosion
in the market town of Omagh.
</P>
<P>
The blast left more than 100 people injured or maimed.
</P>
<P>
Martin McGuinness, the chief negotiator for Sinn Fein, was
quoted by BBC as saying: "This appalling act was carried out by
those opposed to the peace process."
</P>
<P>
"It is designed to wreck the process and everyone should work
to ensure the peace process continues," he said.
</P>
<P>
BBC called the statement "the strongest condemnation of an act
of paramilitary violence by the party which represented the IRA in
the Stormont talks."
</P>
<P>
No group has claimed responsibility for the bomb, which was
planted in a maroon Vauxhall Astra. But local Chief Constable
Ronnie Flanagan said: "Undoubtedly we will be focusing our
attention on those who call themselves the 'Real IRA'. It is
possible and probable that they carried out this attack,"
according to BBC.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
