<HEADLINE> Irish Prime Minister Vows to Suppress Terrorists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern
Saturday night condemned the Northern Ireland bomb blast and
pledged to "ruthlessly suppress" the terrorists behind the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
British police were quoted by BBC Television as saying Saturday
evening the death toll in the Northern Irish town Omagh bombing
has risen to 26 and more than 100 others including five children
were injured.
</P>
<P>
In a strongly-worded statement issued in Dublin, Ahern was
reported as saying that the lastest bombing was a "dastardly"
incident and an "attack on democracy."
</P>
<P>
Ireland's main opposition Fine Gael leader John Bruton called
for an "all-Ireland security initiative that would make the
commissioning of such outrages impossible."
</P>
<P>
Irish President Mary McAleese said that she was deeply shocked
by the terrorist bombing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Gerry Adams of Sinn Fein, political wing of the
Irish Republican Army (IRA), has unequivocally condemned the Omagh
blast.  
</P>
</TEXT>
