<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Bombing Won't Affect Clinton's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The bomb explosion in a
Northern Ireland market town will not change U.S. President Bill
Clinton's plan to travel on September 3 to Belfast, said the White
House on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton planned to visit Northern Ireland after visiting Russia
to celebrate the province's historic peace accord negotiated under
his administration's urging and guidance.
</P>
<P>
At least 25 people were killed in a bomb explosion in Northern
Ireland earlier on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not aware that there would be any changes to the trip as a
result of this" bombing, said White House spokesman P.J. Crowley.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly the people of Northern Ireland and Ireland have chosen
a path toward peace. Violence has no place in that process,"
Crowley added.
</P>
<P>
The bombing, in the crowded market town of Omagh, occurred
some distance away from areas near Belfast where Clinton plans
to visit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
