<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up:  Western Countries Busy Evacuating From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Western countries including
Britain, France, Belgium and U.S are busy evacuating their
nationals from Congo (K) where a military rebellion against the
government has lasted for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Royal marines from the British Navy arrived Saturday by air at
the south Atlantic island of Ascension, 3000 kilometers west of
Kinshasa, ready to intervene or evacuate British nationals if the
situation deteriorates in the rebel-besieged city, a report
dispatched by Deutsche Press Agentur DPA said.
</P>
<P>
DPA quoted a British Defense Ministry spokesman as saying in
London that the 190-strong unit of royal marines is part of 40
commandoes based at Taunton in Somerset.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the British Foreign Office has advised the 300
British nationals in Congo (K) to leave as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The marine unit will remain on standby on Ascension Island and
the Defense Ministry spokesman said that the unit will only be
used if the situation deteriorates further.
</P>
<P>
Fears escalated for the safety of foreign nationals trapped in
the Congolese capital after commercial airlines such as Belgian
Carrier Sabena and South Africa suspended their flights earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
Early Saturday, three French Army Rransall Aircraft arrived in
Brazzaville, capital of the neighboring Congo Republic, from
Gabon to evacuate foreigners from Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
The foreigners being evacuated, number at about 700, include
French, South Koreans, and other nationals, according to Agence
France-Presse AFP.
</P>
<P>
They were escorted in buses toward landing stage on the Congo
River and due to cross the river on a barge for Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
Some 650 soldiers of a battalion of the French troops
stationed in Gabon have been put on alert.
</P>
<P>
However, Brazzaville is separated from Kinshasa by the Congo
River and the river border has been closed by the Kinshasa
authorities for about a week.
</P>
<P>
The French hoped it will be re-opened to facilitate the
evacuation.
</P>
<P>
Also on Saturday, a Belgian aircraft flew to Libreville in
Gabon, about 800 kilometers from Kinshasa to be ready to evacuate
Belgian citizens from Congo (K)
</P>
<P>
"It is on standby for an evacuation of Belgians from Kinshasa,
Belgian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hubert Cooreman said in
Brussels, adding that there are about 3,000 Belgians in Congo
(K), a former Belgian colony,
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that the U.S. flew out 130 foreign
nationals Friday, including around 50 of the total 250 Americans
in the country.
</P>
<P>
During the two-week long Tutis-led rebellion, rebels have
seized the important eastern towns of Goma, Bukaveu Uvira and
Bunia.
</P>
<P>
The rebels said Saturday that they have also captured Matadi,
an important port that controls the flow of food stuffs and other
vital supplies up the Congo River to Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Rebel leader Jean Pierre Ondekane confirmed Friday to Reuters
that the rebel forces have taken Ingara Electric Dam, 250
kilometers south-west of Kinshasa on the lnga River, leading a
20-hour blackout in the capital.
</P>
<P>
And foreign affairs ministers from Zambia, Zimbabwe, Namibia
and Tanzania mandated by a summit attended by seven southern
african leaders including Congolese President Laurent Kabila in
Zimbabwe on August 8, arrived Saturday in Kinshasa after they had
talks in Kigali with Rwanda's Vice-President Paul Kagame on ways
of ending the Congo (K) conflict.
</P>
<P>
Their mission is to broker a peace deal and investigate
Kinshasa's allegations that Rwanda and Uganda have been backing
the rebels, which were denied by both countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
